62
00:03:05,936 --> 00:03:07,062
Good morning.

63
00:03:08,022 --> 00:03:09,815
Are you trying to kill me?

64
00:03:10,691 --> 00:03:12,359
No, I think
you're great.

65
00:03:12,443 --> 00:03:14,445
Then why are you
in my bed?

66
00:03:14,528 --> 00:03:15,654
I couldn't sleep.

67
00:03:15,738 --> 00:03:18,490
Our refrigerator is
making a weird noise.

68
00:03:18,574 --> 00:03:20,117
But so was one
of your nostrils,

69
00:03:20,201 --> 00:03:21,785
so don't expect
me back tonight.

70
00:03:21,869 --> 00:03:23,621
Go home before
I call the police.

71
00:03:23,704 --> 00:03:25,664
You wouldn't call the
police on your Moonpie.

72
00:03:25,748 --> 00:03:27,124
Then I'll call your mother.

73
00:03:27,791 --> 00:03:29,960
That you would do.

74
00:03:30,044 --> 00:03:32,713
And leave my extra key behind.

75
00:03:32,796 --> 00:03:34,924
Aw.

76
00:03:35,007 --> 00:03:36,967
Aw.

77
00:03:43,307 --> 00:03:46,268
Do you know anything about
surviving psychological torture?

78
00:03:46,352 --> 00:03:48,646
Because my family
escaped communist Vietnam,

79
00:03:48,729 --> 00:03:49,915
we have to know about torture?

80
00:03:49,939 --> 00:03:51,565
That was my thought.

81
00:03:52,107 --> 00:03:53,525
Well, you're in luck.

82
00:03:53,609 --> 00:03:54,902
What do you want to know?

83
00:03:54,985 --> 00:03:57,738
I'm being tormented by a sound
coming from our refrigerator,

84
00:03:57,821 --> 00:03:59,657
and I don't know how
to deal with it.

85
00:03:59,740 --> 00:04:02,326
When my uncle was
in a reeducation camp,

86
00:04:02,409 --> 00:04:04,870
he would imagine
disemboweling his torturers

87
00:04:04,954 --> 00:04:06,789
with a bamboo spike.

88
00:04:08,249 --> 00:04:10,834
Maybe I'll just get a book
on refrigerator repair instead.

89
00:04:10,918 --> 00:04:11,919
Okay.

90
00:04:12,002 --> 00:04:13,587
New subject.

91
00:04:13,671 --> 00:04:16,131
Jessica Gieger
wears a black bra.

92
00:04:16,215 --> 00:04:18,509
I saw it through the
sleeve of her shirt.

93
00:04:18,592 --> 00:04:22,012
Not beige, not pink.

94
00:04:22,096 --> 00:04:23,889
Black.

95
00:04:23,973 --> 00:04:25,724
So mysterious.

96
00:04:32,189 --> 00:04:33,274
What are you doing?

97
00:04:33,357 --> 00:04:35,276
I'm going to take apart
the refrigerator

98
00:04:35,359 --> 00:04:37,319
and figure out what's
making that noise.

99
00:04:38,570 --> 00:04:40,406
That is a really good idea.

100
00:04:40,948 --> 00:04:43,242
Usually you're not
supportive of my efforts.

101
00:04:43,325 --> 00:04:44,743
I'm more mature now.

102
00:04:55,379 --> 00:04:57,423
- Hi, Mom.
- What did you do?

103
00:04:57,506 --> 00:05:00,634
Good news. I found out
what part was making that noise.

104
00:05:00,718 --> 00:05:02,261
You have to put
this back together!

105
00:05:02,344 --> 00:05:04,179
Now we're getting
to the bad news.

106
00:05:04,263 --> 00:05:06,390
What made you think
you could fix this?

107
00:05:06,473 --> 00:05:08,642
I'm smart...
and I had a book.

108
00:05:09,268 --> 00:05:11,228
Do you <i>still</i> think
you're smart?

109
00:05:12,313 --> 00:05:13,897
Yes.

110
00:05:14,690 --> 00:05:17,443
I told him not to do it.
He wouldn't listen.

111
00:05:23,741 --> 00:05:25,200
$200?!

112
00:05:25,284 --> 00:05:27,453
It'll be okay.
We'll find the money.

113
00:05:27,536 --> 00:05:28,996
Wait.

114
00:05:29,079 --> 00:05:31,623
The old fridge in the garage.

115
00:05:31,707 --> 00:05:34,335
- What's it...? What was...?
- What's that?

116
00:05:34,418 --> 00:05:37,129
Well, I kind of donated
that fridge to the church.

117
00:05:38,797 --> 00:05:40,841
You know, for the needy.

118
00:05:41,383 --> 00:05:42,509
Are you kidding me?

119
00:05:45,012 --> 00:05:47,681
I see tense moments like this
more than you think.

120
00:05:49,391 --> 00:05:51,310
I'll just give you guys
some space.

121
00:05:55,356 --> 00:05:57,775
You know how much it's gonna
cost to fix that fridge?

122
00:05:57,858 --> 00:06:00,235
$200. I have
really good hearing.

123
00:06:01,111 --> 00:06:04,907
Do you have any idea how hard
I work for the money we get?

124
00:06:05,824 --> 00:06:06,867
I'm sorry.

125
00:06:08,827 --> 00:06:10,579
I don't care how long it takes.

126
00:06:10,662 --> 00:06:13,540
You're gonna pay me back
every cent of this.

127
00:06:13,624 --> 00:06:15,042
Yes, sir.

128
00:06:15,125 --> 00:06:18,379
I am very disappointed in you.

129
00:06:26,720 --> 00:06:29,390
You know if you cry,
I can't enjoy your pain.

130
00:06:54,873 --> 00:06:55,874
Mom,

131
00:06:55,958 --> 00:06:58,168
since Sheldon cost you
all that money,

132
00:06:58,252 --> 00:07:00,129
who's your new favorite...
me or Georgie?

133
00:07:00,212 --> 00:07:01,964
You know I don't
have favorites.

134
00:07:02,047 --> 00:07:03,424
Yeah, right.

135
00:07:03,507 --> 00:07:07,261
Okay, whoever takes the trash
out first is my favorite.

136
00:07:07,803 --> 00:07:08,971
She thinks we're stupid.

137
00:07:10,722 --> 00:07:12,224
Dad, I'm pleased
to tell you

138
00:07:12,307 --> 00:07:14,309
I've got a job to
pay back my debt.

139
00:07:14,393 --> 00:07:15,811
Is that so?

140
00:07:15,894 --> 00:07:17,521
I'm going to be a paperboy.

141
00:07:18,856 --> 00:07:21,066
Well, that's great.

142
00:07:21,150 --> 00:07:22,401
I'm proud of you.

143
00:07:22,484 --> 00:07:24,278
How do you plan
on delivering these papers?

144
00:07:24,361 --> 00:07:27,156
- Bicycle.
- You don't know how to ride a bicycle.

145
00:07:27,239 --> 00:07:28,991
There's nothing I can't learn.

146
00:07:29,074 --> 00:07:32,369
A week ago, I didn't know how
to take apart a refrigerator.

147
00:07:33,829 --> 00:07:35,914
He can't deliver newspapers.

148
00:07:35,998 --> 00:07:38,000
- Why not?
- It's too dangerous.

149
00:07:38,083 --> 00:07:39,877
I think you're being
a little overprotective.

150
00:07:39,960 --> 00:07:43,255
You expect him
to go riding around at 5:00 a.m.

151
00:07:43,338 --> 00:07:46,091
with cars and dogs
and who knows what else?

152
00:07:46,175 --> 00:07:48,218
I did it when I was his age.
So did Georgie.

153
00:07:51,180 --> 00:07:53,891
You're gonna teach your brother
how to do this.

154
00:07:53,974 --> 00:07:55,309
What if I don't want to?

155
00:07:55,392 --> 00:07:56,560
You're doing it anyway.

156
00:07:56,643 --> 00:07:58,896
Hey, nobody asked
your opinion.

157
00:07:58,979 --> 00:08:01,482
I knew the answer.
I got excited.

158
00:08:10,032 --> 00:08:12,284
Georgie?

159
00:08:12,367 --> 00:08:13,994
Georgie?

160
00:08:14,077 --> 00:08:15,245
What?

161
00:08:15,329 --> 00:08:18,332
I'm ready to scrub the moral
stain off my character.

162
00:08:20,459 --> 00:08:23,045
I hate everything about you.

163
00:08:30,677 --> 00:08:32,471
When does the truck
bring the papers?

164
00:08:32,554 --> 00:08:34,056
When it does.

165
00:08:34,139 --> 00:08:36,016
That's a tautology.

166
00:08:36,099 --> 00:08:38,018
- What?
- A tautology.

167
00:08:38,101 --> 00:08:40,896
A statement that's true,
but uninformative.

168
00:08:40,979 --> 00:08:43,232
Hey, you're supposed
to be the one teaching me.

169
00:08:43,315 --> 00:08:44,608
That's funny.

170
00:08:46,944 --> 00:08:48,278
Oh, there it is.

171
00:08:48,362 --> 00:08:50,572
Over here! Over here!

172
00:08:50,656 --> 00:08:52,074
This is exciting.

173
00:08:52,699 --> 00:08:53,825
It's somethin'.

174
00:08:57,746 --> 00:09:00,207
Thank you!
Have a great day!

175
00:09:00,290 --> 00:09:01,583
Now what?

176
00:09:01,667 --> 00:09:04,002
Take 'em into the
garage and fold 'em.

177
00:09:04,962 --> 00:09:06,255
Oh, boy.

178
00:09:09,758 --> 00:09:12,886
Fold 'em like this,
then rubber band.

179
00:09:14,304 --> 00:09:16,723
But you didn't fold it
into even thirds.

180
00:09:16,807 --> 00:09:19,142
- Nobody cares.
- I care.

181
00:09:19,226 --> 00:09:21,144
Then do whatever you want.

182
00:09:23,772 --> 00:09:26,316
Wake me up when you're done.

183
00:09:26,400 --> 00:09:28,527
<i>Over the next 17 minutes,</i>

184
00:09:28,610 --> 00:09:32,406
<i>I used physics, geometry
and old-fashioned hard work</i>

185
00:09:32,489 --> 00:09:34,908
<i>to create the perfect
newspaper-folding system.</i>

186
00:09:36,451 --> 00:09:38,078
I'm done.

187
00:09:39,496 --> 00:09:41,373
Great. Let's
load up the wagon.

188
00:09:41,456 --> 00:09:44,209
No, I'm done with this one;
I still have 39 more to go.

189
00:09:51,216 --> 00:09:53,802
He's gonna be fine.

190
00:09:53,885 --> 00:09:55,029
You don't have to tell me that.

191
00:09:55,053 --> 00:09:56,263
I know he's gonna be fine.

192
00:09:56,346 --> 00:09:57,973
If you believe that,

193
00:09:58,056 --> 00:09:59,766
why aren't you in bed right now?

194
00:09:59,850 --> 00:10:02,131
Because this is the same boy
who couldn't find his way out

195
00:10:02,185 --> 00:10:03,812
of that sleeping bag.

196
00:10:03,895 --> 00:10:06,148
He made his way out.

197
00:10:06,231 --> 00:10:09,109
Just took him five
or ten minutes.

198
00:10:09,192 --> 00:10:11,028
I know you're
worried, but...

199
00:10:11,111 --> 00:10:14,698
he needs to experience
the world a little bit.

200
00:10:14,781 --> 00:10:18,076
Why not let him do it
when most of it's asleep?

201
00:10:18,160 --> 00:10:19,870
I suppose you're right.

202
00:10:23,206 --> 00:10:26,084
You coming back to bed?

203
00:10:26,168 --> 00:10:27,544
Are you crazy?

204
00:10:27,628 --> 00:10:29,463
That's my little boy
out there in the dark.

205
00:10:29,546 --> 00:10:33,133
Mm, but your big boy's
right here under the covers.

206
00:10:33,884 --> 00:10:35,177
Ugh.

207
00:10:36,261 --> 00:10:38,597
There is a nicer way
to say that.

208
00:10:40,807 --> 00:10:42,934
All right, you got
your list of addresses?

209
00:10:43,018 --> 00:10:44,895
- Right here.
- 'Kay. All you got to do

210
00:10:44,978 --> 00:10:46,581
is go up to each house
and throw the newspaper

211
00:10:46,605 --> 00:10:47,814
at their front door.

212
00:10:47,898 --> 00:10:49,149
Got it.

213
00:10:49,232 --> 00:10:50,609
All right,
I'm going back to bed.

214
00:10:50,692 --> 00:10:51,693
Thank you, Georgie.

215
00:10:51,777 --> 00:10:53,236
You've been a wonderful teacher,

216
00:10:53,320 --> 00:10:55,447
and I'm very appreciative
that you took the ti...

217
00:10:55,530 --> 00:10:57,741
Ah! My hands are black!

218
00:10:57,824 --> 00:11:00,118
- Why are my hands black?
- Relax.

219
00:11:00,202 --> 00:11:02,120
It's just the ink
from the papers.

220
00:11:02,204 --> 00:11:03,830
Why wasn't I warned of this?!

221
00:11:05,624 --> 00:11:07,668
Out, damned spot.

222
00:11:07,751 --> 00:11:09,836
That's from Shakespeare!

223
00:11:14,716 --> 00:11:16,635
<i>♪♪Oh ♪♪</i>

224
00:11:17,969 --> 00:11:19,805
<i>♪♪Slow ride ♪♪</i>

225
00:11:21,431 --> 00:11:23,850
<i>♪♪Take it easy ♪♪</i>

226
00:11:25,936 --> 00:11:27,521
<i>♪♪Slow ride ♪♪</i>

227
00:11:29,606 --> 00:11:32,234
<i>♪♪Take it easy ♪♪</i>

228
00:11:34,319 --> 00:11:36,238
<i>♪♪Slow ride ♪♪</i>

229
00:11:37,322 --> 00:11:39,908
<i>♪♪Take it easy ♪♪</i>

230
00:11:41,243 --> 00:11:42,244
Aw.

231
00:11:44,621 --> 00:11:45,622
Hey, Sheldon.

232
00:11:45,706 --> 00:11:46,706
Hello, Billy.

233
00:11:46,748 --> 00:11:48,041
Are you our new paperboy?

234
00:11:48,125 --> 00:11:50,127
Yes, I'm joining
the work-a-day world.

235
00:11:50,210 --> 00:11:52,754
I work, too!
I take care of our chickens.

236
00:11:52,838 --> 00:11:54,047
Don't get the wrong idea.

237
00:11:54,131 --> 00:11:56,842
When I grow up, I plan on being
a theoretical physicist.

238
00:11:56,925 --> 00:11:58,301
Cool.

239
00:11:58,385 --> 00:11:59,845
I'm sticking with chickens.

240
00:11:59,928 --> 00:12:01,763
All righty, then.
Have a nice day.

241
00:12:01,847 --> 00:12:03,181
You, too.

242
00:12:03,265 --> 00:12:06,059
Oh, cool, it's Monday.

243
00:12:06,143 --> 00:12:07,519
<i>♪♪Hold me ♪♪</i>

244
00:12:07,602 --> 00:12:09,479
<i>♪♪Roll me ♪♪</i>

245
00:12:09,563 --> 00:12:10,939
<i>♪♪Slow ridin' woman ♪♪</i>

246
00:12:11,022 --> 00:12:12,357
<i>♪♪You're so fine ♪♪</i>

247
00:12:12,441 --> 00:12:14,067
How's he doing?

248
00:12:14,151 --> 00:12:16,862
Been out here 20 minutes.
This is his second house.

249
00:12:19,531 --> 00:12:22,451
He throws like you.

250
00:12:22,534 --> 00:12:23,910
<i>♪♪Slow ride ♪♪</i>

251
00:12:23,994 --> 00:12:25,245
<i>To say this first day</i>

252
00:12:25,328 --> 00:12:27,539
<i>was challenging
would be an understatement.</i>

253
00:12:27,622 --> 00:12:29,958
<i>To say the rest of the week
got better from there would be</i>

254
00:12:30,041 --> 00:12:31,601
<i>the kind of lie
